fields.name: diplomatic
fields.notes: This covers all: ministers, envoys, commissioners, diplomatic agents, charges d'affaires, etc.

fields.name: support staff
fields.notes: all the secretaries or clerks

fields.name: consular
fields.notes: this covers all variations on consul, as well as agents for commerce and seamen, etc.

fields.name: Acting Vice Consul in Charge
fields.notes: "Acting" typically denotes a temporary position, held until the official replacement arrives.  More research is necessary to find out why the one assignment for "Acting Vice Consul in Charge" lasted for 49 years.

fields.name: Agent for Claims and Seamen
fields.notes: Agents typically were not commissioned, however since only one person ever held this title more research is required.

fields.name: Commercial Agent
fields.notes: This title is a curious artifact of the Napoleonic Era. After Napoleon declared himself "First Consul" he required that foreign consuls be retitled in the French Empire.  The Convention of 1800, which ended the Quasi-War, renamed all American consuls in French held ports "Commercial Agents."

fields.name: Commissioner Plenipotentiary
fields.notes: Research needed to verify commission.

fields.name: Consul/ Claims Commissioner
fields.notes: Consuls were commissioned.

fields.name: Consular Agent
fields.notes: Even though this position has Agent in the title, it is clear from years served that this was a permanent position, since technically only American citizens could be commissioned as consuls (though there are many examples to the contrary).

fields.name: Diplomatic Agent
fields.notes: This title appears to have only been used once -- for Charles Dumas.

fields.name: Minister Resident
fields.notes: This appointment came one year after the Portuguese royal family moved to Brazil to escape Napoleon I and made Rio de Janeiro the temporary capital of the Portuguese Empire.

fields.name: Vice /Acting Consul
fields.notes: It appears that those who held this position, were acting as consul while technically holding the position of vice consul (which was rarely a commissioned title).  More research is required into the particulars of each case.

fields.name: Vice Consul
fields.notes: Vice consul was typically an non commissioned post.  However, in some cases Vice Consuls were commissioned.  See the notes for each assignment record to determine if that officer held a commission as vice consul.
I think this is meant to be his time as sole commissioner to Great Britain.  If so, then this record needs to be overhauled or deleted.

fields.name: Commissioners
fields.notes: These Commissioners had their letters forwarded to John Jay during his mission to Great Britain in 1794.  More research is required to determine who they were.

fields.name: Commissioners at Pittsburg
fields.notes: These Commissioners had their letters forwarded to Jay in 1794.  More research is required.  They may be synonymous with the group referred to as Commissioners (id #1).

fields.name: John de Neufville & Son
fields.notes: Wrote to John Jay in 1794.  More research required.

fields.notes: This letter exists in the Jay papers as a facsimile included in a sale record.  The write up of the letter, which gives the date as November 19 is full of errors, and though the image is blurry, the month is better rendered as "Sept" -- to see the letter, look at the associated citation.  Additionally, Monroe makes mention of a previous letter from Jay sent the 24th of the month and Jay wrote to Monroe on that date (A Comprehensive Catalogue of the Correspondence and Papers of James Monroe, pg. 33).  This also appears to be the the first letter Monroe sent to Jay, which makes the November dating even less likely. The Catalogue does not record a letter from Monroe to Jay on September 19 or November 19.
